{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015Dxwt5dtmG92igdhiNuDZ2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Implementation Notes\n     2→\n     3→## Decisions Made\n     4→- Introduced `FlowSemantics` plus `stage_plan_for_flow(...)` so the shared engine can drive `standard`, `docs_change`, and `ci_improvement` without stage-ID branching.\n     5→- Added generic engine entrypoints `execute_run` / `resume_run` and kept the legacy standard-only names as thin wrappers to preserve existing tests and callers.\n     6→- Kept `quick_dev` blocked at the CLI while still defining flow semantics for it, so the engine surface is ready for a later loop without exposing unfinished behavior now.\n     7→- Extended both engine-level and CLI-level tests for docs/CI flows, and corrected the conformance feature text that previously claimed only `standard` was executable.\n     8→\n     9→## Spec Deviations\n    10→- Non-late `ConditionallyApproved` outcomes still do not persist follow-ups in `run.json`. The current canonical model only has the durable amendment queue, and the spec also states docs/CI flows should not queue durable amendments, so I preserved the existing non-blocking behavior instead of inventing a new snapshot field in this loop.\n    11→\n    12→## Testing\n    13→- Verified with `cargo test` using explicit Nix toolchain paths plus `CARGO_TARGET_X86_64_UNKNOWN_LINUX_GNU_LINKER` because the default shell PATH did not expose `cargo` or `cc`.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01GmHc9N8Srjnat2yn1mzYfx","session_id":"216e97eb-aa57-41df-a04f-9831b7c2815e","uuid":"ee7cb045-6024-4f03-a441-632acbf4cef8"}
